dom-which won the 2011 Clarence H. Haring Prize for the Most Outstanding Book on Latin American History-Walter Fraga charts these slaves' daily lives and recounts their struggle to make a future for themselves following slavery's abolition in 1888. Through painstaking archival research, he illuminates the hopes, difficulties, opportunities, and setbacks of ex-slaves and plantation owners alike as they adjusted to their postabolition environment. Breaking new ground in Brazilian historiography, Fraga does not see an abrupt shift with slavery's abolition; rather, he describes a period of continuous change in which the strategies, customs, and identities that slaves built under slavery allowed them to navigate their newfound freedom. Fraga's analysis of how Recôncavo's residents came to define freedom and slavery more accurately describes this seminal period in Brazilian history, while clarifying how slavery and freedom are understood in the present.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aFreedmenzBrazilzBahia (State)xHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveryzBrazilzBahia (State)xHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveszBrazilzBahia (State)xHistoryy19th century. 4aChoice Magazine Outstanding Academic Title. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aMahony, Mary Ann1 aMahony, Mary Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlenes, Robert W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822374558zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822374558423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822374558.jpg  a978-3-11-070808-0  DUK Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_E